      <hedline>
        <hl1>COFFEE CROP DAMAGE</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Jennifer L. Rich</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Rich, Jennifer L</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Severe droughts and unusually cold weather in Brazil's south and southeast could sharply reduce next year's coffee crop, to 25.9 million 60-kilogram bags, from potential production of 35 million bags (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Severe droughts and unusually cold weather in Brazil's south and southeast could sharply reduce next year's coffee crop, to 25.9 million 60-kilogram bags, from potential production of 35 million bags, according to preliminary government estimates. The state of Minas Gerais, which produces about half of Brazil's coffee crop, is expected to lose about a third of its beans this year, while production in Parana, where a recent cold front hit the hardest, may be down 85 percent. Brazil is the world's largest coffee producer.</p>
        <p>Jennifer L. Rich (NYT)</p>
      </block>
